        "THE FERNANDO DE NORONHA ARCHIPELAGO REPRESENTS ONE OF THE AREAS OF GREATEST BIOLOGICAL PRODUCTIVITY IN BRAZILIAN TERRITORY, BEING AN IMPORTANT SITE FROM THE TROPHIC POINT OF VIEW FOR SEVERAL SPECIES SUCH AS TUNAS AND TUNA-LIKE RESOURCES, BUT STILL LITTLE STUDIED IN THE LIGHT OF THEIR TROPHIC ECOLOGY. TROPHIC INTERACTIONS AND FEEDING HABITS AMONG FOUR LARGE PELAGIC FISH: ACANTHOCYBIUM SOLANDRI, CORYPHAENA HIPPURUS, SPHYRAENA BARRACUDA AND THUNNUS ALBACARES, WERE INVESTIGATED THROUGH THE INTEGRATE"@pt ;
