<http://example.com/capes#thesis/19551> a capes:Thesis ;
    capes:hasAbstract "FLUID CATALYTIC CRACKING IS A PROCESS USED IN PETROCHEMICAL INDUSTRIES TO CONVERT HEAVY OIL FRACTIONS INTO LIGHTER FRACTIONS, SUCH AS GASOLINE AND LPG, FOR EXAMPLE. THE CONVERSION OCCURS DUE TO THE INTRODUCTION OF SOLID PARTICLES CALLED CATALYSTS (GELDART'S CLASS A POWDER) INSIDE INDUSTRIAL FCC RISERS. GENERALLY, COLD FLOW PILOT UNITS ARE BUILT FOR THE STUDY OF FLUID DYNAMICS PHENOMENA INVOLVING GAS-SOLID FLOWS IN RISERS. IN THESE UNITS, DIFFERENT TECHNIQUES OF BIPHASIC FLOW EVALUATION ARE APPLI"@pt ;
